column168: Union Pacific Railroad train YST65-1 Delivered 55 cars to tracks 5 and 6 at the Port of Stockton yard, The 24th car in track 5 NATX300775 upon inbound interchange inspection was found to be leaking product from the top of the car. Further inpection found that # 2 and 3 top manyway swing bolts were loose these bolts were tightened and then car was rechecked for leaks and car still was leaking. further inspection found the top manway cover gasket was cut and abraided and the manway gasket was replaced and car rechecked for leaks and found to be ok for movement.  Shipper cable seal was in place and car had not been tampered with.
column169: Contaxct was made with the shipper Western Plains energy Eric Robben and they were advised on proper securment of loaded cars and to be sure and inspect the manway gaskets on each load and to properly tighten manyway cover bolts. Union Pacific railroad also contacted to provide site follow-up

column168: On 7/02/07, container TTNU413228, Sodium Perboraste Monohydrate, 5.1, UN3377, PG III, containing 660 - 50lb bags, shrink-wrapped on pallets (44,842 lbs) was noted leaking by drayman during pick-up. The leak was reported to CSXI Terminal personnel who reponded an emergency response contractor. Six bags were found broken open and leaking. The damaged bags were placed into over pack drums and returned to the container for final delivery. Remediation generated 150 pounds of contaminated product and held at the terminal for proper disposal. The lading was block/brace for final delivery via highway to destination.    Cause of the incident is shipper liability due to no blocking and bracing. Improper loading allowed the lading to shift toward the rear of the container where there was a 4ft void. The bags fell over and broke open.
column169: Follow AAR recommended guidelines for loading, blocking and bracing to prevent loadshift.

column168: BNSF YST103-13 Delivered 26 cars to the CCT at 1330 hours 7-13-07 into track 4 at the Port of Stockton yard. the 11th car in the cut NATX301914 was found to be leaking when inbound mechanical inpsection of the delivery was made.    Inspection of the car found that the leak was coming from the top of the car under the protective housing. Further inspection found seal and pin on housing intact and after opening the housing the 3 inch top load valve assembly was found to be leaking at the bottom flange. The 3 inch valve was loose and could be moved by hand. also the 3 inch and 2 inch plugs on the 3 inch loading valce and 2 inch induction valve were only hand tight. This 3 inch valve and the 2 inch valve had just been changes or repaired as there was fresh teflon tape on the threads.  3 inch valve was tightened by use of a 36 inch pipe wrench to refusal and leak was stopped.  the design of the 3 inch valve and its handle and the 2 inch valve precluded the 3 inch valve from being tightened unless the handle on the 3 inch valve was opened and the 3 inch pipe plug on the valve removed to allow the 3 inch valve to be tightened to refuseal. car was alos overloaded and no proper outage was taken on this shipment
column169: When valves are changed on a car be sure and tighten the vales to refusal and use vales where when applied to the car the valve need not be opened to tighten the valve down.  Proper inspection by the loader when done loading and further training for the loaders. Cotact was made with shipper: Wendy Kostick at Front range on 7-13-07 1742 hours PST to advise of leak, reason and repair.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked allowing approximately 3 pints of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer.  Approximately 1 pint had leaked through the floor of the trailer onto the ground.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 1 gallon steel pail was placed into a 1 cubic yard haz mat box along with various others destined for disposal.  During transportation, the load shifted and crushed the pail allowing the liquid to escape.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it along with the damaged pail at the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the loaders will be re-instructed to insure that containers are loaded in such a way to preclude the potential for smaller containers to be crushed by larger, heavier objects.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: During the outbound inspection of Q62608, a car inspector smelled the odor of ammonia near tank car UTLX 950435, load of Anhydrous Ammonia.  The inspector notified the Frontier Yard Trainmaster and the area was isolated. The TERP plan was initiated. HazMat Mgr. M.C. Bethge was notified to respond and investigate the odor. Upon arrival, M.C. Bethge found the B-End Liquid Line Valve to be leaking vapors between the valve base and the pressure plate around the securement studs. Attempts to tighten the stud nuts were not successful in stopping the vapor leak. CSXT ER Contractor, SPSI, was called to respond with a Midland Cap Kit.  Tank Car UTLX 950435 was switched from outbound Q62608 onto class track #63 and isolated from the yard area. Buffalo Fire Dept. HazMat inspected the vapor leak. Canutec was notified at 0352 hrs report # TLR2007-499, NYS-DEC was notified at 0400 hrs report # 0703929 and the NRC was notified at 0412 hrs. report #841332.  SPSI  capped the b-end liquid valve at 0915 hours on 08Jul07 with a Midlind kit. The rail car was  inspected and pressure was monitored daily.  SPSI returned to Buffalo on 14Jul07 to transfer UTLX 950435. The transfer was completed on 14Jul07 at 1930 hrs. The product was transloaded into TILX 303029. ULTX 950435 will be Home Shopped for Repairs.    Cause Code:  270  NARRI:  2(5+9+0) x (2+0) = 56

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in transit a shipment containing Phosphoric acid released.  The cause of release is unknown.  The shipment contained six, fifteen-gallon plastic drums in which one drum was damaged resulting in a release of approximately fifteen-gallons.  The release was confined to the trailer and has been cleaned up by USF Reddaway. The damaged freight was overpacked and retured to the USF Reddaway terminal for shipper instruction on disposition. No injuries or exposures and agencies were contacted.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Ecolab, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: 09-JUL-2007: Upon receipt of the subject cargo at our CFS warehouse, it was discovered that this shipment was in fact an undeclared/hidden hazmat shipment. The shipment was palletized and overpacked in white shrink wrapping. The packages within were discovered to be properly labeled with a "UN 1266" sqaure-on-point diamond label, but not reflected on the exterior surface of the overpack. Furthermore, no hazardous documentation was presented to our personnel at any time prior to our discovery of this shipment.    Upon notification of this issue, the shipper then provided us with the appropriate hazardous documentation, thus, rendering this shipment compliant with the applicable regulations.    /// END OF REPORT ///

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: When inbound trailer was opened at unloading facility, shipment was discovered with one of four 5 gallon pails lying on it side, between slats of skid.  Pail had large dent in side and pin hole size puncture.  Pail presumably fell off of other pails in shipment, resulting in the breach of the container.  Approximately one pint of contents released.  Spill was contained and cleaned up with absorbent compound.  Damaged pail held in hazardous materials bay for disposal via environmental contractor.
column169: Notice with pictures sent to loading facility to review loading practices, with emphasis on dunnage and blocking and bracing.  Damage could have easily been avoided by placing dunnage or loose freight around pails to keep them from shifting.  Shipment was packaged adequately for transport as received from manufacturer.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 07/18/2007 at 05:55 hours, CSXT Train Master, Dean Connell, Queensgate Yard,reported tank car, GATX 50732, load Hydrochloric Acid, had a cloud of smoke coming from the top of car. The car was isolated at the hump bowl and the Cincinnati Fire Department was notified.  Upon arrival, they shut down the car shop and the hump bowl yard operations sending all CSXT employees to another location of the yard not affected by the vapor cloud. The Hopple Street bridge that goes over the middle of the yard and Spring Grove Avenue that travels in front of the yard were also shut down to non-essential traffic. CSXT emergency response contractor, Veolia Environmental Services, was contacted to respond and seal the tank car. Veolia Environmental Services arrived and made entry at 08:30 and discovered that the 165 lb. rupture disc was blown.  A new 165 lb. rupture disc was installed and a plastic cap was replaced on to the top of the rupture disc assembly.  The car was decontaminated and released on to destination.            NARRI :  2 (5+5+0) * (2+4) = 120    Cause Code = 441
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 7/23/07 at 08:35 hours, the General Car Foreman in Goulding yard, Pensacola, FL., reported tank car JJJX 101, load Anhydrous Ammonia, was leaking vapors from the top of the car. The car was moved to the north end of yard on track PSH for isolation and repairs.  CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS, was dispatched to the scene.  Upon arrival, SWS found a small vapor leak at the pressure relief valve.  The valve cage was removed and retainer cap and O rings were inspected.  One of the O rings appeared to be distorted. A new set of O rings and retainer cap was installed on the valve and the leak stopped. Car was secured and released on to destination.    Cause Code: 413  NARRI:  5 (5+9+2) x (2+0) = 160
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At 17:41, on July 25, 2007, train Q61325, was discovered to have a leaking Carbon Dioxide car in train at Bushnell, FL. The local Fire and Police Department were on scene and reported a loud roaring noise from the top of the tank car UTLX 82625. The train was ordered to stay on location until the car was inspected by SWS, and repairs made if required. SWS arrived and inspected the car and found one of the regulator valves was frozen open and would not shut down. Pressure in car was down to 200 lbs at time of inspection.  Water was applied to the valve to remove the ice build up. This action caused the valve to operate as required and  the train was released by the Fire Department to move forward.     Cause Code: 422  NARRI:  2(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24
column169: No additional comments.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: On 7/17/07 a Univar driver was using a drum dolly to move a 55 gallon poly drum of Sulfuric Acid from the front of his trailer to the rear. When he started moving towards the rear of the trailer he noticed the product leaking from the bottom  side of the drum. The driver quickly stopped and placed the drum on its side with the small hole facing upward to stop the leak.   The driver used Soda Ash to absorb and neutralize the spill. He then placed the clean up material and drum of Sulfuric Acid inside of a recovery drum.
column169: During the investigation it was found that the foot of the drum dolly was bent upward and out. This defective equipment was what caused the damage to the drum. As a result of the findings we took the equipment out of service and are purchasing new.  All drivers have been informed of this incident and a weekly inspection of handling equipment will be performed by them.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: David Bartlett arrived at store around 21:00. The store has 2 NL tanksso he was going to put 3000 gallons of NL that was in Comp 1 into NL tanks #2, and was going to put 2000 gallons that was in Comp 2&3 into tank #1 for NL. Comp2 had 1000 gallon NL and comp 3 had 1000 gallons of NL. He hooked up comp 1 to NL tank 2 and began to unload, then hooked comp 2 to NL tank 1. The rabbit ears hooked to the NL tank 1  wasn't on tight enough and when he pulled the handle the hose popped off the evertite fitting and fuel came out. Right away within seconds Bartlett shut the valve off, and fuel was going down the parking lot. He grabbed all the rags in the valve box and put them on the spill. He saw the fuel going to what he thought was a  drain so he grabbed all the rags that were in the cab of the truck and ran ahead of the fuel that was moving toward the drain and he started to plug the drain with rags. He was able to put the rags in the drain before the fuel reach it. He then called Selma dispatch and was told to call 911 immediately. He called 911 and Bartlett told them that what had happen and to send Fire Dept. After he got off the phone with 911, he then called dispatch back again and was then asked to call Ricky in Fayetteville and have him go to the store with clean up stuff, and to call Ronnie McCoy. At first the driver thought the spill was a 100 gallons or less. Then when the Fire Dept. got there they put this dry on the ground and me and a fireman did measurements of the tank levels and guessed the spill to be about 40 gallons. The Hazmat Captain did his measuremants and said the spill was under 10 gallons. Bartlett said he guess high numbers becasue he wasn't really sure how much was spilt and people kept asking him, so he said 100 gallons or less.    river failed to properly secure hose allowing disconnection and spill of 40-50 gallons.  Contained to asphalt.  Driver protected drain to oil/water separator, but City of Fayetteville environmental department wanted it inspected and flushed if contaminated.  Eastern Environmental inspected the site, removed absorbent materials and verified drain pipe was clean.  Reported to City of Fayetteville who was satisfied.
column169: Driver failed to properly secure hose allowing disconnection. Better training to ensure the equipment is used properly and connected securely would have prevented this incident.

column168: Truck was traveling Northbound on George Owens County Road.  The driver attempted to navigate around three other gravel trucks parked along the shoulder of the road.  In the process of doing so, the trucks left tractor tires slid off onto the soft shoulder and sank into the water saturated soil.  The momemtum and surge of product in the trailer caused the trailer to then overturn. The driver reported the incident and response crews were dispatched to the scene. No product was lost from the cargo tank. A small amount of motor oil and diesel fuel was spilled from the truck. The cargo tank load was transferred to another truck, and the overturned truck and trailer were uprighted. A remediation crew then cleaned up the site.  No further action was required.
column169: The root cause of this accident was that the driver failed to realize the dangers of driving too close to the edge of a gravel road with an unimproved shoulder and the presence of water saturated soils.  Heightened emphasis on edge drop off, weather hazards, and off-road travel safety tips would help in reducing incidents such as this from occuring.

column168: On July 1, 2006, A Huntsman Corp. Shipping Operator was charged with loading a tank truck with JEFFAMINE® T-403. JEFFAMINE T-403 is a product made in a continuous operation from a polyol and ammonia. JEFFAMINE T-403 is used in epoxy applications. The truck to be loaded arrived at the Huntsman Corp. Conroe Site at 2323 hours to load a shipment of approximately 48,000 lbs of JEFFAMINE T-403. The truck is owned by Heniff Transportation Systems, Inc. This shipment was to be made against our order 4570013495. The Shipping Operator lined up the tank and loading equipment to load. He then spotted the truck at the loading site. He performed a preload inspection on the truck and approved it to load. The Shipping Operator attached the appropriate loading hoses and set the meter to load 48,000 lbs as required by the order. The Shipping Operator then started the load. Loading commenced at 2340 on July 1. At approximately 0045 hours on July 2, the Shipping Operator noticed that the product was flowing out of the 3” wash out cap on the top of the tank truck. He immediately went to the loading site and closed a manual valve to stop the spill. A total of 15,764 lbs of product was lost. Based on the amount of product lost, the actual overflow was for approximately 9 minutes. The Operator immediately notified the Lead Operator in Charge. Clean up began immediately. The sewer system was switched to capture the spilled material in our waste water tank. All of the liquid material was captured in our waste water tank. The waste water was then shipped off-site for disposal in a deep well. A root cause investigation was performed on July 6, 2007 and action items were developed to prevent a reoccurrence of a similar incident.
column169: Several action items to prevent a reoccurrence of a similar incident were developed during the incident investigation. The main cause of the incident was that the automatic shut off valve failed to close because a manual/automatic selection switch was not put in the automatic position because the operator was not aware that there was switch. He had loaded many trucks through this same system and had never switched the switch. It was assumed that since there were no earlier incidents, that the switch had previously been in the automatic position. The switch was positioned remote from the meter and it was, therefore, not obvious that there was a switch. The operator reported that he had not been trained to review the switch position on this meter before loading and was notaware that the switch existed. Action items were developed to label the meters that had remote switches so that operators would be reminded of their existence and retrain all operators to ensure that all know the existence of this switch and any other remote switches that might exist in the loading area. In addition, we will investigate the possibility of interlocking the meters with the automatic switches to prevent the start of a load using a meter without the valve being in the automatic position or, if that is not feasible, to move remote switches closer to the meter.

column168: The driver had just finished loading a full load of diesel at Nustar in Stockton, CA on Navy drive deading to deliver load to Schneider, French Camp, CA when entering the southboud on ramp to Interstate 5. The driver was traveling too fast for the turn and the truck rolled over. The driver sustained no injuries and called the dispatch department. A witness called 911 and the California Highway Patrol was dispatched to the scene. Once the incident was reported to dispatch, the dispatch department called the environmental clean up company to contain any spill of product. Approximately 1263 gallons of diesel was spilled onto the highway.
column169: Additional training will be implemented to all new and existing drivers on understanding the importance of knowing your truck. column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED TO HAVE AN ODOR AND UPON  INSPECTION FOUND A VARIOUS ARRAY OF TOOLS AND STUFF USED BY AN ELECTRICIAN WOULD  USE, SUCH AS ELECTRICAL CONNECTORS, ELECTRICAL TAPE, ETC. . ALSO CONTAINED IN  THIS SHIPMENT WERE THREE DIFFERENT AEROSOL SPRAY CANS. THE CAN THAT RESULTED IN  THE SPILL WAS LABELED LPS CFC FREE ELECTRO CONTACT CLEANER, WITH A DANGER LABEL:  EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE. THIS WAS AN 11 OZ. (312 GRAM) AEROSOL SPRAY CAN, WHOSE SPRAY  BUTTON WAS NOT PROTECTED, AND HAD BEEN DEPRESSED AND DISCHARGED INSIDE THE BOX.  THE SECOND CAN WAS A DIFFERENT AEROSOL SPRAY CAN OF 284 GRAMS (10 oz) A RADIO SHACK  BRAND OF VELOCITY DUST REMOVER (NON-FLAMMABLE). THE THIRD CAN IS AN AEROSOL, 128  GRAMS (4.5 oz) ALSO FROM RADIO SHACK AND IS A NON FLAMMABLE GAS, CONTROL/CONTACT  CLEANER AND LUBRICANT. THE SECOND AND THIRD AEROSOL SPRAY CANS DID NOT LEAK.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND WILL CLARK OF THE SF0/FAA OFFICE WAS FIRST NOTIFIED BY  VOICEMAIL AT 12:25 ON FRIDAY JULY 20. WE SPOKE ABOUT THE INCIDENT LATER THAT  AFTERNOON, AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING THE FAA INSPECTION.

ONE PALLET CONTAINING 36-45 POUND TEMIK 15G LOCK LOAD 3H2 CONTAINERS WAS BEING SHIPPED FROM THE SEMINOLE LANE FACILITY. THE DRIVER'S LOAD SHIFTED AND FELL FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, APPROXIMATELY 2/10 OF A MILE FROM THE ORIGIN FACILITY. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PICKED UP THE UNDAMAGED CONTAINERS. SIX (6) OF THE 3H2 CONTAINER HAD THEIR LIDS KNOCKED OFF FROM THE FALL. APPROXIMATELY 60 POUND OF THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ON THE ROAD SURFACE. NO MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. ALBNY POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS HANDLED TRAFFIC CONTROL, SITE SECUREMENT AND RECOVERY OF THE SIX (6) CONTAINERS AND LIDS. A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, RCL ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS DISPATCHED TO RECOVER THE SPILLED GRANULES AND DECONTAMINATE THE ROAD SURFACE.
column169: ON MONDAY, JULY 9,2007, ADDITIONAL REFRESHER TRAINING WAS PROVIDED TO ALL EMPLOYEES AT THE FACILITY. A THROUGH REVIEW OF LOAD SECUREMENT AND BLOCKING/BRACING TECHNIQUES WAS PERFORMED WITH EACH DRIVER. THE STRAIGHT TRUCK INVOLED IN THIS INCIDENT WAS THEN TAKEN TO A LOCAL WELDING SHOP TO HAVE ADDITIONAL CLOSURE PINS ATTACHED TO THE REAR GATES TO ENSURE THE GATES WILL NOT COME OPEN AGAIN DURING MOVEMENT.

column168: A cargo tank was overfilled with hydrogen peroxide when the loader, who is also the carrier, programmed the incorrect amount into the flow meter used to transfer the product from a rail car.  The loader left the area to use the rest room when the transfer was thought to be almost complete.  He did not stop the transfer thinking the meter would shutdown the transfer pump.  Site personnel informed him that the trailer was overflowing product.    Site personnel assisted in diking the estimated 500 gallons of spilled peroxide.  Approximately 6000 gallons of water was added to the diked spill to dilute the hydrogen peroxide until no visible signs of decomposition remained.  The diking material was then pushed over the diluted spill.  No signs of the spill remained approximately 2 hours after the incident.    The spill was reported to the National Response Center and the Oregon Emergency Response System.
column169: Actions taken to prevent recurrences of future incidents include:  - Changing the loading processes to a one step process.  - Incident reviewed with the loader and disciplinary actions taken.  - Loader communicated incident to other loaders / drivers during safety conference call.    Other recommended changes being evaluated to help prevent recurrences of future incidents include:  - The use of a checklist to provide independent verification or a check of the set up prior to starting the transfer.  - Instituting a Behavior Based Safety Audit system.

column169: Rather then loading through the dome lid of the truck, the 3" or 4" clean-out cap at top of cargo tank near dome lid is removed. After loading the reducer is removed and clean-out cap is screwed on (plus cable seal is applied).

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading one poly overpack containing four, 200-liter plastic drums was discovered.  Upon investigation it was determined that one 200-liter drum was damaged and the remaining three were unaffected.  Approximately, 50 gallons of free product were released.  The release was due to a puncture, caused by a forklift accident.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. performed cleanup using absorbent rags, dunnage and PPE.  Cleanup materials, contaminated debris and leaking drum were placed into one, ninety-five gallon drum over pack and seven, fifty-five gallon drums which will be held at H.M.H.T.T.C. for disposition.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrences.  However, Alliance Airlines will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle made a routine stop at a 10-day intransit storage facility pending it's scheduled arrival date at the unloading facility.  While at the intransit facility, it was discovered that a leak had developed within the trailer allowing approximately 55 gallons of material to escape to the floor of the trailer and the gravel parking area.  Facility personnel immediately responded to the release and initiated containment and clean-up activities.  It was determined that a 250 intermediate bulk package developed a leak at the discharge valve.  The container was removed from the trailer and secured and all spill debris was containerized in a suitable container.  Once the response activities were completed, the shipment was delivered to the intended waste management facility for proper disposal.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Houston, Texas on the Madrid Express Voyage 51E23 as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Houston of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.    The shipping papers that accompained the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequentially provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the udneclared hazardous materials onboard.

About 10 minutes into pumping a product from our cargo tank to the customer storage tank, the transfer hose failed and spilled about 5 gallons before the driver could shut down.  The spilled product went into a containment area and was scooped up.  Driver was able to complete the delivery with another section of hose.
column169: The hose had been inspected in the past year.  Our action plan is to continue our process of hose testing in order to cull bad hoses.  We will also investigate decreasing the hose testing interval from 12 months to 6 months.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While unloading a valve malfunctioned on the tank causing approximately 15 gallons of material to release. P Chem personnel applied absorbent pads to contain free product. Milstead Environmental of Spring, TX was contacted to remove the used absorbents. The waste generated from this incident was placed into seven, fifty-five(55) gallon drums pending disposal. Milstead Environmental will coordinate disposal of the waste generated from this incident. The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. personnel will continue to reinforce safety guidlines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: 0108 EST --  A DOT-407 tanker carrying Sodium nitrate was traveling on I-15 Southbound in Las Vegas NV.  The driver made a defensive move to avoid one or more persons in the roadway who were gathering items that fell from a vehicle.  The tractor and trailer left the roadway and overturned laying across the southbound lanes and into the dirt median.  The fire and police departments were summoned to the location.  It is unclear how long it took for the arrival of the first responders and the actions taken to prevent and migration of the product of diesel fuel.      The tractor sustained heavy damage to the driver's side and the fuel tank on the same side was leaking fuel from the cap.  The trailer was laying down an embankment at a 45 degree angle with its nose rising towards the roadway.  HMHTTC called upon H2O to respond to the scene and contain any leaks and transfer the load of sodium nitrate.  Upon their arrival, the response team laid down absorbents near the leaking fuel tank to prevent furthe rmigration of the fuel.  Additionally, they found a minor leak from the washout cap and placed a poly bucket under the cap to contain the leak.  The damage to the trailer was mostly to the outer jacket.  The weather at the time of MVA was clear and dry.     After a effort led by Disttech and HMHTTC, a tanker was located and arrived at 1315 hours to accept the load of sodium nitrate.  The transfer was completed by 1707 hours.  The response team removed the valve assembly on the bottom of the tanker as it was the only accessible spot to remove the product.      After obtaining the markouts for underground utilities and required permits, the response team returned to the site to excavate the contaminated soil.  Upon completion, soil samples were grabbed for analysis.  The soil was replaced, tamped and seed and an erosion blanket placed on top.

column168: At approximately 12:50pm on July 25, 2007 a van trailer stored at Clean Harbors Environmental Services 10-day in-transit storage yard located in Deer Park, TX experienced a minor release of hazardous material from a non-bulk package. An employee at the location noticed small amount of material seeping through the van trailer floor.  He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 55-gallon UN 1A2 container of Class 3 flammable liquid was not properly closed in preparation for transportation.  The lid of the container was not properly secured and permitted escape of the hazardous materials during transportation.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to contain approximately 10 gallons of liquid that was release to the floor of the trailer.   The lid of the leaking drum was repositioned and properly fastened.  All of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.   Approximately one quart of material leaked through the floorboards of the van-trailer onto the concrete containment pad.      All of the released material was collected and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was improper preparation of the package for transportation and insufficient inspection prior to transportation.    The individuals responsible for preparing this shipment for transportation will be informed of this incident and a request will be made to the involved parties to undergo additional training on container closure and inspection.

column168: Driver loaded at TDC and had pressure on trailer that was not released before leaving. Driver stopped at traffic light on N. Pine ST. as he pulled away from traffic light he noticed a spray from the top of trailer (dome lid), immediately stopped to access situation. The vacuum vent valve released due to pressure from liquid sloshing in trailer. Police were notified, arrived on scene and secured area. Police contacted emergency response personnel. TDC was called out to handle clean-up. The spilled product was sprayed with hydrogen peroxide to neutralize odor and product. A shelter in place was issued along with an evacuation of area. Four general public was sent to hospital for evaluation and released. Invoices are not available to give an accurate account of cost.
column169: We have provided additional training to our drivers that they are not to leave any plant with pressure on the trailer. We have also notified this particular shipper, TDC, that our drivers are to relieve pressure from tank before leaving. We also reviewed this policy in Safety meeting to ensure that everyone knows policy.

column169: This was the undeclared DG cargo case.  The customer did not declare their DG cargo, and transit the cargo as non-DG by rail from Midwest to West Coast.  After the cargo was arrived at West Coast, the customer advised to our company(a carrier) that the cargo was hazardous load.  We hired a vanning surveyor.  According to the survey report, the container had no placards on the exterior.  However, the inside of the container; there was a large envelope on the floor marked "MSDS Documents".  It was so obvious that the shipper was aware of the presence of hazardous materials in the shipment.  There were also the palletized bags confirmed that a number were labeled Class 9.  From the technical point, the consignment should be blocked to prevent shifting during the ocean transit further to the final destination via vessel. We informed the customer the result accordingly.  We hope the US authority emphasizes and frequency conducts random check for transport units at anywhere.

column42: NITRATING ACID MIXTURES SPENT WITH NOT MORE THAN 50 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: This load was picked up from the Generator (Schwerdtle Stamp Company) on July 16, 2007 by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. This load was brought back to Clean Harbors Facility located at 51 Broderick Road, Bristol, CT. This load was reloaded along with other wastes in one of our staged empty trailers and its destination was Reidsville, NC. On July 16, Our Driver (Conrod Gillin) picked up the loaded trailer, conducted a pre-trip, and signed the manifests. Mr. Gillin began to drive to his destination which was Clean Harbors Environmental Services located on 208 Watlington Industrial Drive in Reidsville, NC. On July 17, 2007 while traveling South Bound on 1-95 near mile marker 138, a citizen advised our driver that something was leaking out of his trailer. He stopped along the side of the road and discovered a small stream of liquid coming out of the trailer. Mr. Gillin opened the trailer doors, discovering a poly barrel (55gallons) lying over and liquid leaking from a bung hole. Mr. Gillin called dispatch and roiled he barrel over, stopping the leak. The Fredericksburg Fire Department arrived and took over the scene. They determined that the poly drum containing a (Waste Nitrating Acid Mixture Spent) was bulging and had been leaking from the bung hole from around the plug. They placed this drum into an over pack barrel and an environmental clean-up response team (IMS) took responsibility for the scene. In the process of cleaning up the scene, IMS placed 3 additional barrels containing the same solution into over pack barrels because they were bulging. Subsequently, the Fire Department had 1-95 closed for 3 hours during this incident. IMS estimated 15-20 gallons of solution had leaked from the barrel. A post incident Level 1, Commercial Vehicle Safety Check was conducted. This report indicated that the leaking material was improperly packaged and the load was not secured (Properly blocked/braced).  The primary cause of this leak was improper packaging by the hazardous waste generator. The generator placed the waste nitrating acid mixture in a poly (plastic) barrel and it should have been placed into a stainless steel barrel. This mixture expanded (over time and elevating temperatures) causing the barrel to bulge on the sides as well as base which made the barrel wobbly or unstable. Had this material been packaged properly in stainless steel, there would not have been any bulging which would have kept the barrel from rocking. Regardless weather Clean Harbors used better blocking and bracing when loading the trailer, if the barrel fell over it would not have leaked.
column169: We have developed additional training for drivers. This training entails how to use the Code of Federal Regulations, Title 49 to extract information for their loads. This training would cover proper packaging, markings, placarding and shipping papers. We have also advised employees about the  regulations for proper load securement and how this can be achieved by using blocking and bracing.  Schwerdtle Stamp Company (Waste Generator) was notified about the improper packaging. Clean Harbors Environmental Services was also notified about the improper packaging as well as improper load securement.

column42: LIGHTER REFILLS CONTAINING FLAMMABLE GAS NOT EXCEEDING 4 FLUID OUNCES (7.22 CUBIC INCHES) AND 65 GRAMS OF FLAMMABLE GAS
column168: This incident did not involve any accident or failure of any package.  In or about May 2007, certain multipurpose lighters were manufactured in China incorporating newly designed components. A third party surveyor was retained in Hong Kong to survey and report on the subject shipment of multipurpose lighters prior to its embarkation to Savannah, Georgia. The particulars of the survey included a gas leakage test. No gas leakage was detected.  Despite having received confirmation that no gas leakage was detected prior to shipment, in an abundance of caution, arrangements were made to have the container inspected upon its arrival in the Foreign Trade Zone at the Port of Savannah, Georgia. Without opening the container, a sample probe was inserted through the door seals of the container. Air samples were instantly analyzed for the presence of flammable gas.  The container arriving July 19, 2007 tested positive for the presence of a small quantity of flammable gas. A HAZMAT contractor was immediately hired to open and ventilate the container. After thoroughly ventilating the container, individual packages were inspected. No packages had been opened or damaged in any way.  Next, the interior of the packages were monitored for the presence of flammable gas. On July 25, after thorough testing of the inside of the packages indicated no additional gas was leaking, packages were reloaded into the container and sent to the final destination for further testing and evaluation of the lighters.

column168: ON 07/06/07 AM A CHEMICAL SPILL OCCURRED AT PACIFIC COAST WARHOUSE AT 4340 EUCALYPTUS AVE. CHINO CA 91710. THIS SPILLL EMCOMPASSED THE TRAILER, FRONT DOCK AND ONTO THE CONCRETE BY THE UNLOADING DOCK. THE CHEMICAL WAS MERGAL 186 (CORROSIVE, FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, NOS. CONTAINS DIMETHYLOXAZOLIDINE, CLASS 8(3), UN2920, PACKING GROUP 2. THE WAREHOUSEMAN HAD STARTED UNLOADING PALLETS FROM THIS INBOUND, WHILE ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD THE 3RD PALLET HE NOTICED LIQUID ON FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER, AS A RESULT OF JUST PUNCTURING DRUM WITH FORK. THE REAR LEFT DRUM TOWARD THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER HAD BROKEN THROUGH TOP BOARDS OF PALLET AND WAS RESTING AT FLOOR LEVEL. THE WAREHOUSEMAN ENTERED FRONT OF THE PALLET, LEFT FORK PUNCTURED DRUM ON THE SIDE OF THE BODY OF THE DRUM, 1" FROM THE BOTTOM. HE PROCEEDED TO EXIT THE CONTAINER TO THE FRONT DOCK, THERE HE NOTICED THE LIQUID WAS COMING OUT OF ONE DRUM OF THE FOUR HE HAD ON THIS PALLET. HE PUT A MASK ON AND TOLD A SECOND WAREHOUSEMAN TO RETRIEVE SOME CHEM.-DRY TO HELP CONTAIN SPILL. HE THEN PLACED A CALL TO UPPER MANAGEMENT AND EXPLAINED WHAT HAD HAPPENED. MANAGEMENT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, PULLED MSDS SHEETS AND DRIVER'S SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911 TO DISPATCH FIRE DEPARTMENT. WAREHOUSEMAN RETRIEVED OVER PACK DRUM AND PLACED LEAKING DRUM ABOVE OVER PACK DRUM TO STOP FURTHER SPILLAGE. ALL EMPLOYEES EXITED WAREHOUSE AND WAITED FOR FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ARRIVE. SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS THEN NOTIFIED. CHINO FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 8:50 AM, EVACULATED OFFICE WORKERS AND DRIVER'S FROM ENTIRE FACILITY. CHINO FIRE DEPARTMENT EVALUATED & VENTILATED THEN CLEARED FACILITY AT 12:00 PM. PACIFIC COAST WAREHOUSE CONTACTED A LICENSED BUSINESS TO CLEAN UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE. FOUR WAREHOUSEMEN AND ONE DRIVER WERE TAKEN TO CHINO MEDICAL CENTER, DIAGNOSED, TREATED AND RELEASED, NO ONE WAS ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL. column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HWY 95 IN UTAH WHEN A CAR TRAVELING IN THE OTHER DIRECTION WAS IN DRIVERS LANE OF TRAVEL. DRIVER SWERVED TO RIGHT TO MISS CAR AND TRUCK AND LEAD TRAILER WENT OFF THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER, DRIVER THEN TRIED CORRECTING TO BRING TRUCK AND LEAD TRAILER BACK ON THE ROAD WHEN THE FORCE OF THE OIL IN THE PUP TRAILER PULLED THE TRUCK AND LEAD TRAILER OVER SLIDING THEM ACROSS ROAD INTO A CLIFF. THE OIL LOST FROM THE LEAD TRAILER WAS DUE TO THE IMPACT OF ROLLING ONTO ITS SIDE AND SLIDING DOWN THE ROAD. THE PUP RUPTURED DUE TO IMPACT OF THE CLIFF. IT TOOK PROBABLY LESS THAN AN HOUR TO LOOSE THE OIL FROM THE TRAILERS. THERE WAS NOTHING THE DRIVER COULD HAVE DONE TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE OF THE OIL. THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LAST WAS 253 BARRELS. THE DRIVER EVACUATED THE WRECKED TRUCK AND SECURED THE AREA AS BEST AS POSSIBLE AND THEN WAITED FOR HELP. THIS HIGHWAY IS A REALLY REMOTE HIGHWAY WITH NO CELL SERVICE SO DRIVER WAITED FOR A PASSERBY TO GET TO CELL SERVICE TO CONTACT 911 AND DRIVERS COMPANY OWNER. THE FIRST EMERGENCY RESPONSE TOOK 3 HOURS FROM WHEN THE INCIDENT FIRST HAPPENED. FIVE TRUCKS, MEDICAL HELP, AND WRECKERS WERE ALL DISPAATCHED TO THE SCENE WHERE IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS TO CLEAN UP ACCIDENT. COMPANY OWNER OF WRECKED TRUCK CMAE AND ASSESSED THE INCIDENT AND THEN PUMPED OFF THE REMAINING CRUDE OIL OUT OF TRAILERS.

column169: DRUMS CONTAINING CHEMICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVED ORIGIN. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF! RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICAL. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USING PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column169: LOCATIONS RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.

4 drums on a pallet that was blocked and braced with load locks, one drum fell off the pallet onto a sharp object in trailer and put a hole in the side.  The driver was coming over the bridge west bound on I-10 when he heard a loud noise in the trailer.  Driver was close to the terminal and when we   opened the door the drum was laying on it's side.  I was able to put some oil dry on the floor to soak up the liquid, let it dry and then washed it out.  We put it in a salvage drum and delivered what  was left in the drum, about 1/2!

column168: At approximately 0350 hours on 07-05-2007 a mechanical car inspector was inspecting train # X539 which was just yarded by the Chicago, FT Wayne and Eastern Railway (CF&E) and during subsequent inspection noted the smell of ammonia. Car Inspector made notification to on duty Trainmaster who is trained through the Incident Commander level who subsequently responded and together with the Car Inspector were able to identify the rail car as GATX 9343 containing Ammonia Anhydrous, UN 1005. Trainmaster in accordance with “Emergency Response Guidelines” cleared the area and created a safety zone in accordance with the guidelines. Trainmaster remained on scene to ascertain extent of vapor emanating from car and noted very, very little odor and notified “Chemtrec”. Riverdale (Illinois) Fire Department was contacted and responded to scene with Truck Company, EMS and Hazardous Material Response Team. Indiana Harbor Belt (IHB) Flazardous Material Officer and Chief Hazmat Officer of Fire Service inspected car and noted a slight odor vapor emanating from the enclosed dome. Chief Hazmat Officer for Fire Service reported to Riverdale Fire Chief his findings who subsequently ordered a clear zone in accordance with Hazmat protocol around the railcar. IHB Hazmat Officer contacted Shipper and Contractor “Sun Pro Services” who subsequently responded to scene and upon inspecting under dome cover discovered Pressure Relief Deviice (PRD) with a very minor leak. Further investigation revealed a bad “0” rings under “0” ring lid which were subsequently changed along with “0” ring lid and leak was stopped. Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) Inspector, Ann Monroe also on scene.  During subsequent investigation into rail car it was determined that car was delivered in error to IHB railroad by the CFE railroad.
column169: During course of event, substantial corrosion was noted inside dome cover and inside “0” ring lid containing the “O”rings. Notification was made to GATX Corporation, Lawrence Scott at 312-621-6209 who was advised of the condition of the car and dome with the suggestion that once car is off loaded, a through inspection should made prior to any further loading. Mr. Scott agreed with IHB Hazmat Officer’s request and will handle. Shipper PCS was also notified of IHB Hazmat Officer Findings and also agreed to facilitate inspection.  The shipper was advised to contact Tanner Industries and have car weighed on arrival so that an accurate determination could be made as to the extent of product loss.

ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGE 5 OFCHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BECOMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: Intermodal ramp personnel reported product odor emanating from intermodal tank container HOYU 241295 (AAR U621) that just arrived on an inbound BNSF intermodal train from the Port of Los Angeles. HOYU 241295 was removed from the well flatcar it was riding on and placed onto a chassis. HOYU 241295 was carefully moved to the contaminated area. Further inspection of HOYU 241295 revealed product drups from the jacketed seam at the bottom of this tank container. The leak source from the inner shell could not be determined. Arrangements were made to procure another suitable tank container for product transfer and it arrived at 1430 hrs. CDT on 7/14/07. The container lift moving the containers into position for the product transfer got stuck in the mud and transfer operations were postponed until the next morning (7/15/07). BNSF contract responders partially transferred contents of HOYU 241295 into the transfer tank container until the product dripping from HOYU 241295 stopped by 1330 hrs CDT, 7/15/07. Spillage a top the rail flatcar was remediated. The contract responders completed full product transfer on 7/23/07.

THE SPECIFIC LOCATION OF THE LEAK IN THE TANK COULD NOT BE OBSERVED BECAUSE OF THE JACKET. UPON INSPECTION BY TOM ROBINSON, UPRR MGR HAZMAT MGMT, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE THROUGH THE SHIPPER, DOW CHEMICAL FOR UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, A CONTRACTOR TO TANSFER THE LADING INTO TANK CAR GATX 48514. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT AND THE CAR WAS KEPT OVER THE CONTAINMENT UNTIL THE DRIPPING LADING STOPPED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DOW AT PLAQUEMINE, LA.

JONES ADVISED NO EXPOSURES OR INJURIES WERE REPORTED. THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGEMENT, WAS NOTIFIED.    INSPECTION REVEALED THE TANK CAR WAS EMITTING AN ODOR DUE TO LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS. TWO OF THE EIGHT BOLTS WERE LOOSE TO THE TOUCH. GATX 201180 was isolated in the railyard. BNSF and shipper contract responders reported that the 280.5 psi pressure relief device (PRO) atop GATX 201180 was the odor source. Contract responders changed out the PRO valve seat o-rings by 1030 hrs. CDT,7/07/07. After the o-rings were replaced and the PRO valve stem was seated, no further product odor was evident emanating from the PRO. Theo-rings removed were hard and grooved from compression.

column168: During an outbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard, the inspector reported NATX 29749 leaking product on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected NATX 29749 finding the liquid valve leaking from the valve stem area. The liquid valve's removable handle was still attached onto the valve stem and when the protective housing cover was closed, the valve handle contacted thehousing cover which forced the handle downward, opening the valve. The responder closed the valve, removed the handle and stopped the product release by 1430 hrs. CDT 7/06/07. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Seal numbered 869925 was removed and replaced by BNSF seal numbered 7013036.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UTLX 208134 with a minor product slosh emanating from the manway cover area during rail car movement in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 208134 and found that all the manway securement bolts were 1/2 turn less than tool tight; which allowed product to escape from between the manway nozzle gasket and the manway cover. The responder properly tool tightened all manway bolts in the required tightening pattern, thusly eliminating any further product release. All spillage rapidly evaporated with no reported ground impact.

column168: Selandras Villanueva, Manager of Yard Operations, reported a tankcar was smoking in the Strang Railyard in La Porte, TX. Tim O’Brien, Regional Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. At 02:52 AM, Villanueva advised Tankcar RCRX 1285 was not smoking, however; it had released a minimal amount of product. State and federal regulatory agencies were notified. At   04:28 AM, O’Brien advised he had inspected the tankcar and found a number of loose fittings, however the fitting thought to be the cause of the release was a loose quick fill port. Mr. O’Brien stated all loose fittings were secured. Mr. O’Brien further advised that the car department would move the tankcar in daylight hours to ensure the integrity of the fittinps. At 07:45 AM, Empress Stevenson, Manager Yard Operations, reported Tankcar RCRX 1285 was bumped and was still releasing a small amount of product. Geoffrey Reeder, Environmental Site Remediation, was notified and responded. Reeder inspected the car and found all fittings appeared tight. Some liquid was visible on the manway. The seal was taken off the fill port and the nut tightened. Seals CTS 2113, 2123, and 2121 were placed on the fitting. Not finding a source of the release, Reeder had a switch engine couple Into the car. The coupling force revealed the manway as source of the release. The 20 bolts on the manway were tightened. The switch engine again coupled into the car and there was no release. The car was released for normal movement. The shipper was notified.

column168: During a BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard, ACFX 89660 was reported with a slight product drip from the bottom of this two compartment tank car. A BNSF contract responder was called to inspect ACFX 89660. The responder reported that no product was observed actively dripping from ACFX 89660 during his initial assessment. The responder's detailed inspection revealed the A-end manway cover was not secured, as all eightmanway securement bolts were barely hand tight. A residue product stain was on the shell under this manway nozzle. The responder properly secured the A-end manway cover. The bottom outlet valves for both the A and B-ends were found closed and secured. The bottom outlet cap (BOC)on the A-end was too! tight. The BOC on the B-end was tight but showed signs of leakage. This BOC was carefully removed for inspection. It was found full of product. The BOC gasket appeared in good condition. The BOC was cleaned, reapplied and tool tightened. A small amount of spillagethat was found under the B-end BOC was absorbed with paper towels. No product leakage was subsequently observed and response wasconcluded by 2300 Mrs. CDT, 7/28/07.

column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection in a railyard departure track revealed GATX 12403 (DOT 111A100W5) leaking product at the bottom of this tank car. A receptacle was placed under GATX 12403 until a detailed inspection was made. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 12403 and concluded that a corrosion hole in the shell from a failed liner was the leak source. GATX 12403 was carefully moved and isolatedin the railyard. Larger pool type receptacles were placed under GATX 12403 while it awaited product transfer. Shipper responders transferred lading from GATX 12403 into another suitable tank car by 0100 hrs. CDT, 7/10/07 without further incident. Responders neutralized ground spillage(estimated at less than 5 gallons) with soda ash. A patch was applied to the tank shell at the small hole near the bottom sump area.The residue heelin GATX 12403 was also neutralized and purged. FRA-07070208 movement approval was granted to send GATX 12403 to a qualified repair facility. Responders also neutralized all captured spillage (estimated between 200-250 gallons) and removed the neutralized solution for appropriatedisposal.

FRA-07070214 movement approval was granted to return GATX 22274 to the origin shipper facility to becleaned and purged prior to sending GATX 2221A to a qualified repair facility.

column168: BNSF mechanical personnel reported UTLX 201089 in the railyard with product spillage on its tank shell that appeared to be coming from themanway area. UTLX 201089 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF contract responders found all eight manway securement boltsloose (three only hand tight and five less than tool tight). Manway cover seal CPC183555 was removed and the manway gasket was inspected.Responders replaced the manway gasket as the former gasket may have been slightly damaged. The manway cover was then properly secured andsealed. A small six inch square product spot was wiped and all other spillage evaporated. No ground impact from spillage was evident. No furtherleakage was observed during subsequent rail car movement. Response was concluded by 2330 hrs. CDT, 07/31/07.

column168: AT 01:33 PM ON 7-12-07, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC, AND ADVISED THAT JAMES HALEY, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR UTLX 71168 LOCATED ON TRACK 201, SETTEGAST YARD: HOUSTON, TX. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED. MGR LERCH RESPONDED AND REQUESTED THE RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC. ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE ASSEMBLY ONTO THE ROADBED. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL 1/16 OPEN, AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP LOOSE...TURN. UPON SLOCING THE VALVE AND TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, AND THE CAR SECURED THE FURTHER RELEASE. AT APPROXIMATELY 02:15 PM, MGR LERCH WA CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER, MERISOL USA AND SPOKE TO RANDY SHILLING, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER. UPON ADVISING MR. SHILLING OF THE NOTED EXCEPTIONS, AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN, HE REQUESTED THAT THE CAR BE RETURNED BACK TO ITS POINT OF ORIGIN FOR FURTHER HANDLING.    THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED, AND BILLED BACK TO ITS POINT OF ORIGIN WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO FURTHER REMEDIATION REQUIRED, AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.
column169: MAKE SURE ALL VALVE AND FITTINGS ARE PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURE. CONDUCT A PROPER POST INSPECTION OF THE CAR PRIOR TO RELEASING FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: At 12:28 AM on 7-10-07, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC and advised that Mario Villegas, Manager of Yard Operations, had reported a possible release of product from tank car UTLX 643194 at the Settegast Railyard, Houston, TX. Mr. Villegas stated the car was isolated at the north end of Track 203. Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch advised theRMCC that he was aware of the incident and that there was a vapor release of product. Mgr. Lerch further stated the tank car hadbeen isolated with no threat of injury to employees, and that the car would be repaired during daylight hours. After inspection of the carat 08:08 AM, Mgr. Lerch noted one of eight manway swing bolts to be in position, not wrench tight, and the vacuum relief valve was leaking vapor due to a failed O-ring. Mgr. Lerch tightened the manway swingbolt one turn. Mgr. Lerch then contacted the shipper, South Coast Terminal Plant, and spoke to Frank Layne, Rail Coordinator advising him of the noted exceptions. Mr. Layne then made arrangements to have the car inspected by plant personnel.At 02:00 PM the car was inspected by South Coast Terminal Plant personnel, and determined that the vacuum relief valve would have to be replaced. Arrangements were made to have a mobile rail carrepair unit respond the next day to replace the valve. At 01:13 PM on 7-11-07, Watco Mobil Railcar Repair arrived on site and replacedthe vacuum relief valve. Car was then released to continue onto destination without further incident.

column25: DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE, US ARMY FORT DRUM
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: At 09:00 hours on 23July2007, a contractor for the Department of Defense at Fort Drum, US Army installation, was loading containers onto COFCrailcars, when two of the flatcars DODX 48816 & DODX 48914, loaded with a total of 19 containers rolled out of the military installation and became"runaway railcars". The two flatcars traveled approximately 4.7 miles from Fort Drum to Watertown, NY. impacting a CSX Rail Gang working on thesingle mainline track at milepost QM 73.8 The runaway railcars struck four pieces of track equipment, two Spike Pullers, a Personnel Carrier and aRubber Tire Track Crane. The Personnel Carrier was attached to a burning cart with two 100 pound LGP (Propane) tanks, which received minordamage during impact. The Watertown Fire Department upon arrival investigated the incident, noticed two US Army containers placarded"Explosives 1.4", called for a mandatory 0.5 mile evacuation. The US Army EOD Team with the Jefferson County HazMat Team removed the two100 pound LPG tanks and the area was re-opened to residents and businesses at 1130 hours. Containers USAU 002787 & USAU 002777placarded "Explosives 1.4" were loaded with blasting/detonator caps and small arms ammunition. Of the 19 containers, 7 had placarding affixed.USAU 018842, USAU 018868 and USAU 002949, Class 2, Non-Flammable Gas & 5.1 Oxidizer (Oxygen Cyclinders Medical Grade), SVVVU 287177,Class 2 Flammable Gas and TEXU 365525, Class 3 Flammable Liquid. All the containers were inspected by the US Coast Guard for blocking andbracing and secured with USCG seals. There were no leaks or release of products from the containers. Cars were re-railed and returned to FortDrum for inspection.-

column168: THE DELIVERY DRIVER FAILED TO USE PROPER OFFLOADING PROCEDURES WHILE ATTEMPTING TO LIFT AN IBC CONTAINER WITH A FORKLIFT FROM THE FLOOR OF A FLATBED TRAILER TO THE GROUND. THE DRIVERS FAILURE TO USE PROPER LIFTING TECHNIQUES NECESSARY FOR A SAFE REMOVAL OF THE IBC FROM THE TRAILER TO THE GROUND RESULTED IN A LOSS OF CONTROL OF THE IBC. THE IBC THEN FELL FROM APPROXIMATELY FOUR FEET, OR THE TRAILER FLOOR LEVEL, TO THE GROUND. THE FALL CAUSED THE IBC TO BREAK APART UPON IMPACT WITH THE GROUND; THUS RESULTING IN AN UNPLANNED RELEASE OF SODIUM HYPOCLORITE ONTO THE GROUND. THE DAMAGE TO THE IBC WAS SIGNIFICANT, CAUSING MULTIPLE LARGE SPLITS IN THE IBC SIDEWALLS.
column169: A RETRAINING OF ALL FACILITY DRIVER/WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEES HAS BEEN CONDUCTED. THIS TRAINING COVERED THE PROPER LIFTING TECHNIQUES OF IBC'S WHEN USING FORKLIFTS. IMPROPER USAGE AND CONSEQUENCE WAS ALSO DISCUSSED DURING THIS TRAINING SESSION. ADDITIONALLY, ALL INVENTORIED IBC'S HAVE BEEN STENCILED WITH "NO FORKS" ON THE SIDES OF THE IBC'S NOT DESIGNED FOR LIFTING WITH FORKLIFTS.

column168: RE: Incident report World Class Products Shipment / Re-Gen Del. 7-25-2007 at approximately 5:50 PM   Received a message from MEl driver, John Amer informing MEl project manager, Ted McCutcheon, that he had a release of Ferrous Chloride Solution material from his acid trailer #THL34 and tractor TR3 during the unloading at the Re-Gen plant in Warren Ohio.   7/25/07 6:00 PM - Tim Dobrosky & Ted McCutcheon returned the call to John Amer to complete the necessary inquiries about the release. During this call MEl management collected information about the size of the area contaminated during the discharge, type of surfaces impacted and what emergency corrective action were taken to contain the spilled product. MEl management also spoke to the plant manger of RE-GEN Mike Cantelmo and Franz Mullings environmental office for Re-Gen regarding the release and to verify the amount of material that was released both inside and out of the unloading containment pad. At this time MEl management was informed that the employees of ReGen, in conjunction with WCI personnel had spread out lime and sand on the affected areas of the release to contain and neutralize the material and to minimize additional contamination from occurring.   7/25/07 — 6:20 PM MEl project manager, Ted McCutcheon, Placed a call to the generator of the Ferrous Chloride Solution, WorldClass Processing Ambridge PA, that was being transported by MEl truck acknowledging that MEl was aware of a problem our driver had encountered during offloading at the Re-Gen facility and that we were in contact with our driver, the plant manager of Re-Gen as well as there Environmental office Franz Mullings regarding the cleanup efforts of this release.   7/25/07 6:30 PM   Conference call was placed to Franz Mullings & Mike Cantelmo by Tim Dobrosky & Ted McCutcheon to discuss remedial activities that needed to be addressed and collect information to complete and put into action MEl Contingency Plan. Franz Mullings did advise MEl that materials that were cleaned up at this site would need to be handled as a K062 waste for disposal. This was mandated by Re-Gen’s operational permit for this site.   Franz Mullings advised Mike Cantelmo to collect several soil samples, draw a map of the area where the samples were taken and test the PH of the soil to verify neutralization of the material was successful. Material used during the cleanup was scraped up by WCI front-end loaders and piled up in the parking area. MEl inquired to the amount of material that they had piled up so a roll off container could be sent to the site by MEl for this material to be placed into it. Mike Cantelmo could not find the stocked piled material and was going to get in contact with the WCI environmental department & transportation department to determine where the material had been taken.
column169: McCutcheon Enterprise Inc., in conjunction with Re—Gen Inc. assistance, are in the process of changing the fittings and hose connections on out tank traits to remove tire need for the transition fitting to adapt to the unloading station. This will provide a direct connection to the unloading station at the site.   All hoses will be inspected prior to their use and will be removed from service if any signs of stress or fatigue are evident.   The driver will remain at the control of the off loading vessel, with access to the emergency shut off to prevent off loading should the situation warrant it.   Additional offloading procedures have been reviewed with MEl drivers   regarding the offloading of similar products.

column168: ON THURSDAY JULY 19TH 2007 A DIAL OIL COMPANY TRACTOR TRAILER WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLL OVER ACCIDENT.  OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON IR59 MM37 SIX MILES OUTSIDE OF KAYENTA ARIZONA WHEN THE TRUCK DRIVER FELL ASLEEP AND DROVE OFF THE ROAD.  THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND ON TO THE GUARD RAIL WHICH PUNCTURED AND RIPPED HOLES IN THE FRON THREE COMPARTMENTS.  THIRTY ONE HUNDRED GALLONS WAS LOST OUT OF THE THE COMPARTMENTS ON TO THE ROAD AND SHOULDER.  THE TWO REAR COMPARTMENTS WERE DRILLED ON LOCATION BY OUR TEAM AND THEN THE TRUCK WAS TOWED BACK TO OUR YARD.  ENVIROTECH WAS CALLED IN TO BEGIN SOIL TESTING AND TO START THE CLEAN UP.  THERE WAS MORE THAN 15 HUNDRED YEARD OF CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVED FROM THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND REPLACED WITH CLEAN SOIL.  AFTER ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED TESTING OF THE ASPHALT WAS DONE TO DETERMINE THE INTEGRITY OF THE ROADWAY.  AFTER TESTING WE DECIDED TO REMOVE MORE THAN 200 FEET OF BOTH LANES OR ROADWAY AND OVER 400 FEET OF SHOULDER AND REPLACE IT ALL.  ALL WORK HAS BEEN COMPLETED IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL RESERVATION ROAD DEPARTMENTS AND EPA.  ALL DRIVERS WILL BE GOING THROUGH DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND FATIGUE TRAINING TO ENSURE THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.
